	<paragraph>
		<heading>
			<size>2</size>  Overview 
		</heading>
		<paragraph>  A Control is a window which provides a means of interacting with the  application. For example, the <link><url>../../reference/controls/WEL_EDIT_chart.html</url><label>WEL_EDIT</label></link> control provides  a user with the means of entering and modifying text. There are many common controls available within this cluster,  each with a specific use. Click 
			<link>
				<url>/libraries/wel/reference/controls/index.xml</url>
				<label>here</label>
			</link> to browse the controls cluster. 
		</paragraph>
		<note>
			<bold>Note:</bold> Each control inherits from <link><url>../../reference/controls/WEL_CONTROL_chart.html</url><label>WEL_CONTROL</label></link>  which is a descendent of <link><url>../../reference/windows/WEL_WINDOW_chart.html</url><label>WEL_WINDOW</label></link> This provides the control with a  large number of general features (including full window functionality). Each control also provides its own feature set which give access to  specific properties of that control. 
		</note>
		<heading>
			<size>2</size>  Creating controls 
		</heading>
		<paragraph>  Each type of control generally has its own creation procedure that is specific to the type of control. For example, <link><url>../../reference/controls/WEL_SCROLL_BAR_chart.html</url><label>WEL_SCROLL_BAR</label></link>     has two creation procedures; make_vertical      and make_horizontal. Depending on which of these two     creation procedures used, you will get a scroll bar aligned vertically or horizontally.  </paragraph>
